post_text:
Nationwide and in California as a whole, responses to the 2020 Census are on track, as more than 62% of households have responded online or by phone, or by mail if they received a paper questionnaire in the mail or on their doorstep.

However, as of July 29, just 57.1% of Lynwood residents have responded among the state’s 480 incorporated cities. And for every person who does not respond, the California Department of Finance estimates that state and local governments will lose out on $1,000 a year in federal funding tied to population for the next 10 years. Now more than ever, your response to the 2020 Census matters. So, if you haven’t responded, please do so today, and urge your family, friends, and neighbors to respond too! For more info, visit https://2020census.gov/en/ways-to-respond.html

post_text:
The District held an emergency board meeting to address building improvements at Lynwood High School. Here is the update:

Lynwood Unified School District held an emergency board meeting on June 24 to discuss a plan of action for improving the 5000 building under repair at Lynwood High School. The Board determined that the District will hire independent structural engineers to assess the building and the rest of the school to ensure structural integrity and safety. Lynwood High has been visited by the Department of State Architecture and independent inspectors.
.
“We will continue to pursue the very best improvements to our building structure that ensure a safe environment for students and staff,” LUSD Superintendent Gudiel R. Crosthwaite said. “We’re committed to strengthening our campus and creating a new standard of excellence at LHS.”

post_text:
Update on today’s building malfunction at Lynwood High:

We’re happy to learn that the issue was limited to a portion of one floor. We are undergoing an inspection from the Department of State Architecture and a structural engineer to assess the building as well as our entire campus. This will allow us to ensure safety and improve our structure over the summer. For the time being, we have closed much of our campus and will limit access while we work toward restructuring. #safetyfirst

post_text: A statement from Lynwood High School today. We'll continue to work through the summer to ensure safety for our students and staff.
shared_text:
Lynwood High School
June 16 at 7:25 PM ·

Lynwood High School Community,

Today at approximately 9 a.m. a portion of the 5000 building on our campus collapsed. We are pleased to report that no one was injured. Two parked vehicles did sustain damage in the incident. We have contacted our building contractor and are in the process of assessing the cause of the issue and evaluating all building structures on campus. Above all else, we want to ensure that our facilities remain safe for our staff and students. While the damage was limited and the safety of personnel was preserved during this incident, we take this very seriously and are working to prevent future concerns. Out of an abundance of caution, we will keep all staff out of the area of issue and will continue to limit staff on campus while we work with our facilities experts. Please know that we are dedicated to making sure our school is a safe and secure environment for all of us. If you have any questions please do not hesitate to reach out to me.
text:
A statement from Lynwood High School today. We'll continue to work through the summer to ensure safety for our students and staff.

Lynwood High School
June 16 at 7:25 PM ·

Lynwood High School Community,

Today at approximately 9 a.m. a portion of the 5000 building on our campus collapsed. We are pleased to report that no one was injured. Two parked vehicles did sustain damage in the incident. We have contacted our building contractor and are in the process of assessing the cause of the issue and evaluating all building structures on campus. Above all else, we want to ensure that our facilities remain safe for our staff and students. While the damage was limited and the safety of personnel was preserved during this incident, we take this very seriously and are working to prevent future concerns. Out of an abundance of caution, we will keep all staff out of the area of issue and will continue to limit staff on campus while we work with our facilities experts. Please know that we are dedicated to making sure our school is a safe and secure environment for all of us. If you have any questions please do not hesitate to reach out to me.

post_text:
Lynwood Unified School District will serve breakfast and lunch at five school sites between 8 to 10 a.m. beginning Tuesday, March 17 available Mon. - Fri. during the duration of the dismissal period.

Meals will be obtained through a drive-through service or walk-up for families without vehicle transportation. Children must be physically present to receive a meal. All meals will be taken offsite to decrease the risk of spreading germs.

Meal pick-up locations:

Lynwood High School
4050 E Imperial Hwy,
Lynwood, CA 90262
In the back of the campus, off of Harris St. Drive-up/walk-up

Firebaugh High School
5246 Martin Luther King Jr. Blvd, Lynwood, CA 90262
Front parking lot drive-up/walk-up

Cesar Chavez Middle School
3898 Abbott Rd,
Lynwood, CA 90262
Front parking lot drive-up/walk-up

Rosa Parks Elementary
3900 Agnes Ave,
Lynwood, CA 90262
Parking lot drive-up/walk-up

Helen Keller Elementary
3521 Palm Ave,
Lynwood, CA 90262
Student drop off area drive-up/walk-up

Read more: https://buff.ly/3daUfum

post_text:
Here is the public health update from the CA Dept of Public Health's Website: https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/OPA/Pages/NR20-017.aspx

Let’s remember to be accurate and responsible with the information we share to the community as we work to keep Lynwood safe.

157– Positive cases (this does not include passengers from the Grand Princess cruise ship currently docked in Oakland)

Of all the confirmed positive cases:

Age 0 – 17: 2 cases
Age 18 – 64: 91 cases
Age 65+: 60 cases
Unknown: 4 cases

24 – Cases of positive tests related to federal repatriation flights

133 – Cases not related to repatriation flights

50 - Travel-related
30 - Person to person
29 - Community transmission
24 – Under investigation

post_text:
Important Message on Student Safety:

On Thursday, October 10, 2019, there was a verbal altercation between two Lynwood High students. A classroom teacher intervened and physically restrained one of the students. The District immediately removed the teacher from the classroom and contacted local law enforcement. The teacher remains on administrative leave while the district works closely with law enforcement to assist them in their thorough investigation. The Lynwood Unified School District does not condone physical violence in any form and takes this matter very seriously. We are fully committed to ensuring all of our schools are safe and secure learning environments for our students, families, and staff.
